('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'A restaurant has 12 round tables, seating up to 5 guests each, with at least 1 guest per table. If 25 guests are seated, what''s the greatest possible number of tables seated with exactly 5 guests?', '["1", "2", "3", "4"]'::jsonb, 2, 'With k tables full at 5 and the rest at minimum 1 guest: 5k + (12−k) ≤ 25. Solving, k=4 needs at least 28 guests (too many); k=3 needs at least 24, leaving 1 extra guest to distribute — it fits. Max is 3. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'A gym had 42 members at the end of week 1, growing by an average of ''n'' members per week. If membership was 97 at the end of week 12, what is n?', '["5", "6", "7", "8"]'::jsonb, 0, 'From week 1 to week 12 is 11 weeks of growth: 42 + 11n = 97 → 11n = 55 → n = 5. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'A steel tube''s wall thickness ''t'' (in mills) must be between 101 and 105, inclusive. Which represents the allowable values of t?', '["|t \u2212 103| \u2264 2", "|105 \u2212 t| \u2264 4", "|t \u2212 101| \u2264 4", "|103 \u2212 t| \u2264 4"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The midpoint of 101 and 105 is 103, and the allowed range extends 2 in each direction: |t − 103| ≤ 2. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'Researchers want to find the optimum amount of sunlight for a new plant''s growth, keeping soil and water constant across 5 pots. What is the best experimental design?', '["Conduct the experiment in the Amazon forest only", "Conduct the experiment in a glass house with ability to control sunlight", "Conduct the experiment in the US but in a natural forest", "Any one of the above"]'::jsonb, 1, 'To isolate sunlight as the variable being tested, you need a controlled environment (like a glass house) where sunlight amount can be precisely varied while everything else stays constant. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'Six people (Abe, Bob, Camila, David, Emily, Frank) were born in 2000–2005, one per year. Abe was born before Bob but after Camila. Bob was born in 2003. Emily and David are both younger than Frank. Which must be true?', '["Frank is older than Bob", "Emily is younger than David", "Abe is older than Frank", "Bob is younger than Emily"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Camila and Abe both fall before 2003, using 2 of the 3 years in {2000,2001,2002}. Since Emily and David must both be younger than Frank, Frank can''t be stuck with the later years {2004,2005} — he must take the leftover early year, making Frank older than Bob (2003). ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'Five applications of a pesticide failed to rid an area of mites — only the most resistant mites survived each time, and their offspring resisted even more effectively. What conclusion best fits?', '["The mites that survived each exposure grew more resistant with each application", "The pesticide was formulated to kill the mites in one application", "The pesticide application did not coincide with the mating season of the mites", "Resistance to the pesticide is passed from parent to offspring"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Offspring of survivors being more resistant than their parents is a direct sign that the resistance trait is heritable — passed from parent to offspring. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'How many real solutions are there for the equation x⁶ = x²?', '["none", "one", "two", "three"]'::jsonb, 3, 'x⁶ − x² = 0 → x²(x⁴−1) = 0 → x²=0 or x⁴=1. Real solutions: x=0, x=1, x=−1 — three solutions. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'In a circuit, a light bulb is wired so that either of two switches (S1 or S2), in parallel, can complete the loop on its own. Which switch settings make the light glow?', '["Close S1 only", "Close S2 only", "Close both S1 and S2", "All the above except opening both"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Since S1 and S2 are parallel paths to the same bulb, closing either one (or both) completes the circuit — only leaving both open keeps the bulb off. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'A red-painted 6×6×6 cube is cut into unit cubes. How many unit cubes have no more than one face painted red?', '["56", "112", "160", "168"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Cubes with 1 painted face: 6(n−2)² = 6(16) = 96. Cubes with 0 painted faces: (n−2)³ = 64. Total with ≤1 face painted: 96 + 64 = 160. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'What is the smallest number of cuts needed to create 64 unit cubes from a 4×4×4 block of wood, if you''re allowed to restack the pieces between cuts?', '["12", "10", "8", "6"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Restacking lets each cut double along one dimension; you need ⌈log₂4⌉=2 cuts per dimension × 3 dimensions = 6 cuts total. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'Of several six-square nets shown, how many fold up into a valid cube?', '["None", "one", "two", "three"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Checking each net for valid cube-folding (no overlapping faces, correct hexomino shape), three of the four shown fold into a proper cube. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'In a gear train, the center gear has 12 teeth and the large wheels on either side have 30 teeth each. If the left wheel spins at 10 rpm, what is the rpm of the right wheel?', '["50", "25", "10", "5"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Left wheel (30 teeth, 10 rpm) drives the center gear (12 teeth) at 10×30/12=25 rpm, which drives the right wheel (30 teeth) back down to 25×12/30=10 rpm — matching the left wheel by symmetry. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'In a gear train A→B→C→D→E where Gear A rotates counter-clockwise, which direction does Gear E move?', '["Clockwise", "Counter-clockwise", "In either direction", "Cannot be determined"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Every other gear in a meshed gear train shares the same rotation direction. Gear E, being an even number of steps removed from A along the chain, ends up rotating the same direction as A: counter-clockwise. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'A wooden sphere is cut 6 times, all the way through a common axis, each cut 30° from the last. How many pieces result?', '["16", "12", "8", "6", "Cannot be determined"]'::jsonb, 1, '6 evenly-spaced cuts through a common axis produce 2×6 = 12 wedge-shaped pieces. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Two 2-Ohm resistors R1 and R2 are in parallel between terminals a and b. Terminal b is connected to c, and two more 2-Ohm resistors R3, R4 are in series between c and d. What is the net resistance between a and d?', '["8 Ohms", "6 Ohms", "5 Ohms", "4 Ohms", "3 Ohms"]'::jsonb, 2, 'R1∥R2 = 1 Ohm. R3+R4 in series = 4 Ohms. Since b and c are joined, total = 1 + 4 = 5 Ohms. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'A circuit combines two AND gates (fed by inverted and non-inverted a, b) into an OR gate — a standard XOR construction. If a=1 and b=0, what is output S?', '["0", "1", "either 0 or 1", "cannot be determined"]'::jsonb, 1, 'This circuit computes a XOR b. For a=1, b=0: 1 XOR 0 = 1. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'A state budget pie chart shows Electricity 9%, Roads 9%, Dairy 6%, Others 17%, Agriculture 59%. What is the sector angle for Roads?', '["68.2\u00b0", "52.7\u00b0", "45.6\u00b0", "32.4\u00b0"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Sector angle = 9% × 360° = 32.4°. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'A bar graph shows how students get to school: Bus=5, Taxi=1, Bike=3, Train=2, Car=6, Walk=5. As a pie chart, what angle (to the nearest degree) represents students who walk?', '["82\u00b0", "73\u00b0", "67\u00b0", "54\u00b0"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Total students = 22. Walk angle = 5/22 × 360° ≈ 81.8°, rounding to 82°. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'A company''s value increased 50% in year one and decreased 50% in year two. What is the net percentage change?', '["0%", "15% increase", "25% decrease", "35% decrease"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Net factor = 1.5 × 0.5 = 0.75, a 25% decrease from the original value. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Mona drove to her sister''s house at 60 mph and returned at 40 mph over the same distance. What was her average speed for the round trip?', '["50 mph", "48 mph", "45 mph", "42 mph", "None of these"]'::jsonb, 1, 'For equal distances at two speeds, average speed is the harmonic mean: 2(60)(40)/(60+40) = 4800/100 = 48 mph. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'Briana and Charlie have 5 sons attending 4-year colleges. Ned (eldest) starts this year, 2 years ahead of Kevin (middle). Larry (youngest) starts 3 years behind Kevin. For how many years will at least one son be in college?', '["6", "7", "8", "9", "11"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Ned enrolls years 0–3, Kevin (starts year 2) enrolls years 2–5, Larry (starts year 5) enrolls years 5–8. Combined, at least one son is enrolled continuously from year 0 through year 8 — 9 years total. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'A 520-gallon tank starts empty with Valve 1 open (7 gal/20 sec). At 9:10 Valve 3 (drain, 3 gal/10 sec) opens, and at 9:20 Valve 2 (8 gal/15 sec) also opens. Both valves opened at 9:00. At what time is the tank full?', '["9:24 am", "9:28 am", "9:32 am", "9:36 am"]'::jsonb, 1, '9:00–9:10 (Valve 1 only, 21 gal/min): fills to 210 gal. 9:10–9:20 (Valve1−Valve3 = 3 gal/min net): +30 gal → 240 gal. From 9:20 (V1+V2−V3 = 35 gal/min net), remaining 280 gal takes 8 min → full at 9:28 am. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'In a 3×3 grid with values a, b, 14 / c, 11, d / e, 15, 10 arranged by a hidden numeric pattern, what is b?', '["5", "7", "12", "13"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Following the grid''s numeric pattern, b works out to 7. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Which of four graphs shows an inverse variation relationship between two quantities?', '["A straight line through the origin with positive slope", "A steep line through the origin in a different quadrant", "A curve approaching both axes without touching them (hyperbola)", "A line with negative slope not through the origin"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Inverse variation (xy = k) produces a hyperbola-shaped curve that approaches, but never touches, both axes. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'How many real solutions does the equation w³ = w⁸ have?', '["one", "two", "three", "None", "Infinite"]'::jsonb, 1, 'w⁸ − w³ = 0 → w³(w⁵−1) = 0 → w=0 or w⁵=1 (real solution w=1). That''s 2 real solutions: w=0 and w=1. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Monroeville''s population was 1,720 in 2010 and increases 10% every 5 years. What is the approximate net percentage change in population by 2025?', '["25%", "29%", "33%", "37%"]'::jsonb, 2, '2025 is 15 years (3 five-year periods) later: growth factor = 1.10³ = 1.331, a 33.1% increase. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'What is the maximum number of 3-inch wooden cubes that fit in a 2 ft × 1.5 ft × 1 ft box?', '["124", "148", "175", "192"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Convert to inches: 24×18×12. Cubes per dimension: 24/3=8, 18/3=6, 12/3=4. Total = 8×6×4 = 192. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'What is the maximum number of 8×6×4 inch blocks that fit in a 2 ft × 1.75 ft × 1 ft box?', '["25", "30", "35", "40"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Convert box to inches: 24×21×12. Orienting the 8-inch side along the 24-inch side (3 exact), the 6-inch side along the 12-inch side (2 exact), and the 4-inch side along the 21-inch side (5 fit, some waste) gives 3×2×5 = 30 blocks — the best of the tested orientations. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'Three boxes are labeled ''calculators'', ''i-phones'', and ''calculators and i-phones'' — but all labels are wrong. Which box(es) must you open to correctly relabel all three?', '["Box marked ''calculators''", "Box marked ''i-phones''", "Box marked ''calculators and i-phones''", "Any one of the three boxes", "Any two of the three boxes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Since every label is wrong, the box marked ''calculators and i-phones'' can''t actually be mixed — it must be a single item. Opening just that box reveals its true content, letting you deduce the other two by elimination. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'Umar feels tired and cold after jogging. Sam heard 18% of the school has the flu. Umar asks if that''s really what''s going on. What''s the most logical reply?', '["Let''s hope you do not have it", "Maybe Umar. But, perhaps not", "You have a 18% chance of having it", "You definitely have the flu"]'::jsonb, 1, 'The symptoms described could have many causes besides the flu. The honest, logical answer acknowledges the uncertainty rather than jumping to a conclusion. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Ben invested $8,000.00 in an account that grows 10% per year. What is the value at the end of year 4?', '["$11,200.00", "$11,712.80", "$5,248.80", "$10,648.00"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Compound growth: value = $8,000.00 × 1.10^4 = $11,712.80. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'In a gear train A→B→C→D→E→F where Gear A rotates clockwise, which direction does Gear F move?', '["In either direction", "Cannot be determined", "counter-clockwise", "clockwise"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Every meshed gear alternates direction from the one before it. Gear F is 5 steps from Gear A, so it ends up rotating counter-clockwise. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'An item is on sale for 35% off. Elena paid $26.00 for it. Let p represent the regular price. What was the regular price?', '["$35.10", "$19.26", "$40.00", "$16.90"]'::jsonb, 2, '65% of the regular price p equals the sale price: 0.65p = $26.00, so p = $26.00 / 0.65 = $40.00. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'How many lines of reflective symmetry and centers of rotational symmetry does a isosceles trapezoid (non-parallelogram) have?', '["1 lines of reflective symmetry and no center of rotational symmetry", "3 lines of reflective symmetry and no center of rotational symmetry", "0 lines of reflective symmetry and one center of rotational symmetry", "2 lines of reflective symmetry and no center of rotational symmetry"]'::jsonb, 0, 'A isosceles trapezoid (non-parallelogram) has 1 line(s) of mirror symmetry, and does not map onto itself under a partial rotation, giving no center of rotational symmetry. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'Three boxes are labeled ''cats'', ''dogs'', and ''cats and dogs'' — but all labels are wrong. Which box must you open to correctly relabel all three?', '["Box marked ''dogs''", "Box marked ''cats''", "Box marked ''cats and dogs''", "Any one of the three boxes"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Since every label is wrong, the box marked ''cats and dogs'' can''t actually be mixed — it must hold only one item type. Opening just that box reveals its true content, letting you deduce the other two by elimination. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'What is the maximum number of 2-inch wooden cubes that fit in a 2 ft × 2.5 ft × 3 ft box?', '["3243", "3420", "3228", "3240"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Convert to inches: 24×30×36. Cubes per dimension: 24/2=12, 30/2=15, 36/2=18. Total = 12×15×18 = 3240. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'What is the maximum number of 4-inch wooden cubes that fit in a 1 ft × 1.5 ft × 3 ft box?', '["105", "120", "108", "124"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Convert to inches: 12×18×36. Cubes per dimension: 12/4=3, 18/4=4, 36/4=9. Total = 3×4×9 = 108. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Kira drove to a friend''s house at 50 mph and returned along the same route at 30 mph. What was the average speed for the round trip?', '["40 mph", "37.5 mph", "50 mph", "30 mph"]'::jsonb, 1, 'For equal distances at two speeds, average speed is the harmonic mean: 2(50)(30)/(50+30) = 37.5 mph. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'A cube assembled from 216 unit cubes (6×6×6) is cut at a 45° angle starting from one of its edges. How many unit cubes are cut in the process?', '["25", "42", "6", "36"]'::jsonb, 3, 'For an n×n×n cube (n=6), a 45° diagonal plane cut starting along one edge slices through n² = 36 unit cubes. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'Yusuf feels a mild headache after a long day. Quinn heard 12% of the school has a migraine condition. Yusuf asks if that''s really what''s going on. What''s the most logical reply?', '["Maybe Yusuf. But, perhaps not", "Let''s hope you do not have it", "You have a 12% chance of having it", "You definitely have a migraine condition"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The symptoms described could have many causes besides a migraine condition. The honest, logical answer acknowledges the uncertainty rather than jumping to a conclusion. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'An item is on sale for 30% off. Wesley paid $21.00 for it. Let p represent the regular price. What was the regular price?', '["$16.15", "$27.30", "$14.70", "$30.00"]'::jsonb, 3, '70% of the regular price p equals the sale price: 0.70p = $21.00, so p = $21.00 / 0.70 = $30.00. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'What is the maximum number of 3-inch wooden cubes that fit in a 1 ft × 1 ft × 1.5 ft box?', '["96", "92", "99", "112"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Convert to inches: 12×12×18. Cubes per dimension: 12/3=4, 12/3=4, 18/3=6. Total = 4×4×6 = 96. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'What is the maximum number of 2-inch wooden cubes that fit in a 2 ft × 2 ft × 2 ft box?', '["1872", "1716", "1731", "1728"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Convert to inches: 24×24×24. Cubes per dimension: 24/2=12, 24/2=12, 24/2=12. Total = 12×12×12 = 1728. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'A pie chart sector represents 38% of the data. What is the sector''s angle?', '["146.8\u00b0", "114\u00b0", "128.8\u00b0", "136.8\u00b0"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Sector angle = percentage × 360° = 38% × 360° = 136.8°. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Zoe drove to a friend''s house at 45 mph and returned along the same route at 35 mph. What was the average speed for the round trip?', '["40 mph", "39.4 mph", "35 mph", "45 mph"]'::jsonb, 1, 'For equal distances at two speeds, average speed is the harmonic mean: 2(45)(35)/(45+35) = 39.4 mph. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'What is the maximum number of 4-inch wooden cubes that fit in a 1 ft × 2 ft × 2 ft box?', '["126", "108", "111", "105"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Convert to inches: 12×24×24. Cubes per dimension: 12/4=3, 24/4=6, 24/4=6. Total = 3×6×6 = 108. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'A company''s value increased 25% in year one and decreased 15% in year two. What is the net percentage change over the two years?', '["6.2% increase", "40% decrease", "10% increase", "10% decrease"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Net factor = 1.25 × 0.85 = 1.062, a 6.2% increase. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'A sphere is cut 7 times, all cuts passing through a common axis, evenly spaced. What is the greatest number of pieces possible?', '["16", "7", "13", "14"]'::jsonb, 3, 'n cuts through a common axis produce 2n pieces (like a pizza cut through the center). For n=7: 2×7 = 14 pieces. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'Sam worries about being selected for the championship. Ben tells Sam, "You''re one of the most talented people at playing the violin, and everyone who is talented gets a spot, so you''ll certainly get a spot." Assuming Ben''s premise about Sam''s talent is true, is the conclusion true?', '["Probably false, but may be true", "Cannot be false", "Cannot be true", "Probably true, but may be false"]'::jsonb, 1, 'If ''everyone talented gets a spot'' (universal) and Sam is talented, then logically Sam must get a spot — this is a valid syllogism, so the conclusion cannot be false. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'A company''s value decreased 30% in year one and increased 25% in year two. What is the net percentage change over the two years?', '["55% increase", "5% decrease", "12.5% decrease", "5% increase"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Net factor = 0.7 × 1.25 = 0.875, a 12.5% decrease. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Ben invested $10,000.00 in an account that grows 8% per year. What is the value at the end of year 3?', '["$12,400.00", "$11,664.00", "$7,786.88", "$12,597.12"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Compound growth: value = $10,000.00 × 1.08^3 = $12,597.12. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Umar invested $1,000.00 in an account that grows 5% per year. What is the value at the end of year 4?', '["$1,200.00", "$1,157.63", "$814.51", "$1,215.51"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Compound growth: value = $1,000.00 × 1.05^4 = $1,215.51. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'Hassan feels a scratchy throat in the morning. Nina heard 25% of the school has a cold going around school. Hassan asks if that''s really what''s going on. What''s the most logical reply?', '["Let''s hope you do not have it", "You definitely have a cold going around school", "Maybe Hassan. But, perhaps not", "You have a 25% chance of having it"]'::jsonb, 2, 'The symptoms described could have many causes besides a cold going around school. The honest, logical answer acknowledges the uncertainty rather than jumping to a conclusion. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'What is the maximum number of 4-inch wooden cubes that fit in a 2 ft × 2.5 ft × 3 ft box?', '["372", "378", "420", "408"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Convert to inches: 24×30×36. Cubes per dimension: 24/4=6, 30/4=7, 36/4=9. Total = 6×7×9 = 378. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'What is the maximum number of 2-inch wooden cubes that fit in a 1 ft × 2.5 ft × 3 ft box?', '["1614", "1620", "1710", "1623"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Convert to inches: 12×30×36. Cubes per dimension: 12/2=6, 30/2=15, 36/2=18. Total = 6×15×18 = 1620. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'How many real solutions does the equation x^7 = x^2 have?', '["three", "none", "four", "two"]'::jsonb, 3, 'x^7 − x^2 = 0 → x^2(x^5−1) = 0 → x=0 or x^5=1. Since 5 is odd, x^5=1 has 1 real solution(s). Total: 2. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Brookline''s population increases 8% every 5 years. What is the approximate net percentage change in population after 10 years?', '["21%", "16%", "12%", "17%"]'::jsonb, 3, '10 years is 2 periods of 5 years: growth factor = 1.08^2 ≈ 1.166, a 17% increase. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'A 240-gallon tank starts empty. Valve 1 fills it at 20 gallons/minute. After 3 minutes, Valve 2 (a drain) opens and removes 5 gallons/minute while Valve 1 stays open. How many minutes after the tank starts filling does it become full?', '["15 minutes", "14 minutes", "12 minutes", "17 minutes"]'::jsonb, 0, 'In the first 3 min, 60 gallons fill up, leaving 180 gallons. Once Valve 2 opens, net rate = 20−5 = 15 gal/min, so the remaining 180 gallons take 12 more minutes. Total = 3 + 12 = 15 minutes. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'An item is on sale for 30% off. Sam paid $35.69 for it. Let p represent the regular price. What was the regular price?', '["$50.99", "$46.40", "$24.98", "$27.45"]'::jsonb, 0, '70% of the regular price p equals the sale price: 0.70p = $35.69, so p = $35.69 / 0.70 = $50.99. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Brookline''s population increases 15% every 5 years. What is the approximate net percentage change in population after 10 years?', '["30%", "36%", "27%", "32%"]'::jsonb, 3, '10 years is 2 periods of 5 years: growth factor = 1.15^2 ≈ 1.322, a 32% increase. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'How many real solutions does the equation a^7 = a^2 have?', '["four", "two", "three", "none"]'::jsonb, 1, 'a^7 − a^2 = 0 → a^2(a^5−1) = 0 → a=0 or a^5=1. Since 5 is odd, a^5=1 has 1 real solution(s). Total: 2. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'Hassan worries about being selected for the science fair. Ben tells Hassan, "You''re one of the most hard-working people at debate, and everyone who is hard-working gets a spot, so you''ll certainly get a spot." Assuming Ben''s premise about Hassan''s talent is true, is the conclusion true?', '["Probably false, but may be true", "Cannot be true", "Probably true, but may be false", "Cannot be false"]'::jsonb, 3, 'If ''everyone hard-working gets a spot'' (universal) and Hassan is hard-working, then logically Hassan must get a spot — this is a valid syllogism, so the conclusion cannot be false. ✓'),
('acl', 'Spatial/Geometric', 'What is the maximum number of 2-inch wooden cubes that fit in a 1 ft × 2 ft × 3 ft box?', '["1290", "1368", "1299", "1296"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Convert to inches: 12×24×36. Cubes per dimension: 12/2=6, 24/2=12, 36/2=18. Total = 6×12×18 = 1296. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Kira invested $5,000.00 in an account that grows 10% per year. What is the value at the end of year 4?', '["$6,655.00", "$7,320.50", "$7,000.00", "$3,280.50"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Compound growth: value = $5,000.00 × 1.10^4 = $7,320.50. ✓'),
('acl', 'Logic/Reasoning', 'Owen feels dizzy after standing up quickly. Priya heard 9% of the school has a blood pressure issue. Owen asks if that''s really what''s going on. What''s the most logical reply?', '["Maybe Owen. But, perhaps not", "You have a 9% chance of having it", "Let''s hope you do not have it", "You definitely have a blood pressure issue"]'::jsonb, 0, 'The symptoms described could have many causes besides a blood pressure issue. The honest, logical answer acknowledges the uncertainty rather than jumping to a conclusion. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'Carla invested $2,500.00 in an account that grows 3% per year. What is the value at the end of year 3?', '["$2,731.82", "$2,281.68", "$2,652.25", "$2,725.00"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Compound growth: value = $2,500.00 × 1.03^3 = $2,731.82. ✓'),
('acl', 'Math/Quant', 'An item is on sale for 25% off. Jamal paid $33.75 for it. Let p represent the regular price. What was the regular price?', '["$42.19", "$27.00", "$25.31", "$45.00"]'::jsonb, 3, '75% of the regular price p equals the sale price: 0.75p = $33.75, so p = $33.75 / 0.75 = $45.00. ✓'),
